The UV–vis absorption spectrum of the CDs (Fig. 2
                        a) showed absorption peaks at 248 and 283 nm, which were attributed to π-π* transitions of aromatic rings, and a prominent absorption peak centered around 363 nm, which corresponds to n-π* transitions of –C = N– bonds formed during the hydrothermal process (Xiahou et al., 2023). The photoluminescence (PL) emission spectrum of a dilute methanolic solution of CDs (20 μg mL−1) showed blue fluorescence upon excitation at 300–420 nm, with maximum emission intensity at 441 nm; the photoluminescence excitation (PLE) spectrum, monitored at the PL peak of 441 nm, showed a peak at 324 nm, which is consistent with the PL spectrum (Fig. 2b and Fig. S3). When the concentration of the methanolic solution of CDs was increased to 200 μg mL−1, the PLE spectrum showed a peak at 510 nm and the PL spectrum showed a peak at 603 nm (red fluorescence) (Fig. 2b and Fig. S4). At lower concentrations (20–80 μg mL−1), the fluorescence emission peak of the CDs was centered around ∼450 nm, whereas at higher concentrations (100–200 μg mL−1), the peak shifted to ∼600 nm. The ratio of fluorescence intensity at 450 nm to that at 600 nm (I450/I600) was calculated to be 15.19, 9.44, 2.93, 0.74, 0.27 and 0.04 for methanolic solutions of CDs with concentrations of 20, 40, 80, 100, 150 and 200 μg mL−1, respectively (Table 1
                        ). These values indicate the co-existence of blue and red emissive species.
